82.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/22115734/Olympic-BMX-prototype-2-speed-derailleur-gears-Meybo-bike_BMX-World-Champion-Twan-van-Gendt_Shimano-Zee-2sp-drivetrain-1068x739.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/22115734/Olympic-BMX-prototype-2-speed-derailleur-gears-Meybo-bike_BMX-World-Champion-Twan-van-Gendt_Shimano-Zee-2sp-drivetrain-607x420.jpg 607w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/22115734/Olympic-BMX-prototype-2-speed-derailleur-gears-Meybo-bike_BMX-World-Champion-Twan-van-Gendt_Shimano-Zee-2sp-drivetrain-100x70.jpg 100w\"></a><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-266260\">48T x 14/16</figcaption></figure><p>His drivetrain consists of two rear cogs moved by an ultra-short cage Shimano Zee M640 rear derailleur, and shifted by what appears to be a Zee 2-Way release shifter mounted upside down on the top, lefthand side of van Gendt’s bar. He’s likely only going to need to hit one shift in the race, so the ergonomics should be easy to manage.</p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/22120137/Olympic-BMX-prototype-2-speed-derailleur-gears-Meybo-bike_BMX-World-Champion-Twan-van-Gendt_Zee-shifter.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/22120137/Olympic-BMX-prototype-2-speed-derailleur-gears-Meybo-bike_BMX-World-Champion-Twan-van-Gendt_Zee-shifter.jpg\" alt=\"Olympic BMX prototype 2-speed derailleur gears Meybo bike, BMX World Champion Twan van Gendt, cockpit\" width=\"1200\" height=\"900\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/22120137/Olympic-BMX-prototype-2-speed-derailleur-gears-Meybo-bike_BMX-World-Champion-Twan-van-Gendt_Zee-shifter.jpg 1200w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoim